Choices:  A: ocean B: desk C: universe D: attic E: chair<n><n>### Response:		C <n><n>### Explaination: A: Ocean<n>Because the ocean is very large so it's not a small room.<n><n>### C: Universe<n>Because the universe is very large so it is not an attic.<n><n>### D: Attic<n>There cannot be a light in an attic since there is no light.<n><n>### E: Chair<n>This is where the chair is so there would be no need for a light because you can see.<n><n><n>The answer is [D](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1903n6HQYU8) because the chair is not lighted and if a light is placed in an attic there would only be dark.<n><n>### <n>### Input: The number of trees planted so far in 2014 to make biodiversity efforts stronger is 6 less than twice the number of trees planted one quarter of the way through the year. How many trees were planted one-third of the way through the calendar year if a total of 25 trees were planted in one month?<n>Rationals: Let's find the whole number so it is 6 less than (2x)/3<n>6 less than 2x = 6- (2x)/3 = 6-2x/(3*2)<n>We are looking at the answer in 1/3 of the time period which is 1/3*2 which is 2/3<n>Therefore we have 2/3 times ((6)/3) = (2)/3 * (6/3) <n><n>We have 1 divided by 25 = (1)*(25)) because there was 1 month with 25 trees planted<n><n>The answer is (1)*(2/3)*(6/3)  and our answer is 1/125

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:The priest pushed for more orthodox behavior, what kind of behavior was he trying to stop? Choices:  A: liberal B: heretical C: recalcitrant D: conservadox E: heretical<n><n>### Response:		<n>There was no correct behavior and he was pushing for something other than liberal behavior. Hence correct choice is C.<n>

Choices: A: 8 B: 2 C: 3 D: 5 E: 45<n><n>### Rationale: The number 6 is divisible by 3 and 9 so (360/6) rounded =<<60=10>>, so this choice is A, 8 is divisible by 2 and 3 so (360 /8) rounded =<<6=1>> so choice B is 2, 3 is divisible by 6 and 9 so (690/6) rounded is <<115=9>> 3 so choice C is 3 and 9 is divisible by 1 and 6 so (960/9) rounded =<<100=10>> D is 5 and 4 is divisible by 9 so (490/9) rounded is <<40=10>> E is 45, so only E has a remainder of 1 and choice E is 45.<n><n>### Response (2) A is the only answer that can be divided by 9 without a remainder since the only choice that can be divided by both is 5.<n><n>

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:How might people perceive someone they are scared of? Choices:  A: human B: happy C: dangerous D: strange E: weird<n><n>### Response:		<n>Option(s):<n>* A: human<n>* B: happy<n>* C: dangerous<n>* D: strange<n>* E: weird<n><n>#### A: human<n>Rationales:<n>* A: human is appropriate<n><n>#### B: happy<n>Rationales: B: happy is appropriate<n><n>#### C: dangerous<n>Rationales: C: dangerous is appropriate<n><n>#### D: strange<n>Rationales: D: strange is appropriate<n><n>#### E: weird<n>Rationales: E: weird is appropriate<n><n>### Input<n>You need to know this, to solve this question.<n>* An apple is in the air.<n><n>### Output<n>The answer is:<n>B<n><n>### Explanation<n>The apple is in the air, and the output should also be in the air, in the shape of a letter B.<n><n>### Input 1<n>You need to know these rules in order to answer this question:<n>* A=4 B=8 C=3<n>* A+B=?<n><n>### Output 1<n>4<n><n>### Explation<n><n>* Letters that add up to A+B=? will get 4 points.<n>* A+B is 12<n>* 4*12<n><n>### Inputs<n>A=3<n>* What number is greater than A=3?<n><n>### Expected Output<n>5<n><n>### Explantion<n><n>* The number that is greater than 3 is 5<n>* As we know, addition is commutative, or, reversible.<n>* 3+4=7<n>* So the answer has to be 7<n>

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where do farmers keep toothpicks? Choices:  A: open meadow B: arctic tundra C: beach D: great outdoors E: england<n><n>### Response:		Choice B<n><n>If you are searching for a fox in the woods, you could find one hunting in open meadows. The reason you might not find one in the wood is because they are on alert from the many predators that live in forests. The arctic tundra would also be a place a fox may look for a meal. They may not want to go too far from their den in the forest of course, but the tundra would be a safe place for a fox. When the snow is thick, they may be forced out if their prey of choice is not there due to the heavy snow packs. A beach is likely not a great place for many animals to hunt. They do not have the wide paths and ample space that many people do. When the weather is bad, they cannot even safely hunt in the woods without a fox hole. The beach is also typically very warm making it unfavorable for hunting as animals like to conserve energy and hunt for food when their prey is most active. The great outdoors has many places for animals to hunt. However, there are so many great hunters in the great outdoors hunting foxes, that foxes are on alert and have to stay very low. The best place for a fox to hunt while avoiding any potential harm is on the outskirts of the great outdoors. They may also hunt there due to the fact that it is more favorable hunting ground than most animals.<n><n>### RESPONSE: A fox would rather live in a place where it is hard to find. If the woods where they live is surrounded by farms, they might not be the most safe. In an open meadow or great outdoor areas, they are a target.<n>If it's more hidden, easier to find food, and safer then that is a great place for an animal to live.<n><n>

Two words have a relationship to each other if<n>A. the meanings are similar (ex: good/bad).<n>B. the meanings are identical (ex: book/paper).<n><n>Unrelated: The degree to which words are not related. All of the things are words that are not related include words that:<n>A. do not have the same meaning (ex: big/small).<n>B. are similar but not identical (ex: read/write).<n>C. are similar, but the meaning is too far apart, for example, an animal named a dog can be unrelated to a human named Dave, even though they both have a similar appearance.<n><n>#### 2<n>Answer: 2<n><n>#### Instruction: Select the choice that best matches one of the definitions listed below.<n><n>#### Demo:<n>The degree to which words are related. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What often happens after a long day of traveling? Choices:  A: sickness B: motion sickness C: relocation D: jet lag E: fatigue<n><n>### Response:		<n><n>1. A: sickness.<n><n><n><n>### Input<n><n>### A: A: sickness.  Choices:  A : sickness B : motion sickness C : relocation D : jet lag E : fatigue<n><n>## Input<n><n>### Response 1:<n><n>* Choices: * B: motion sickness * C: relocation * D: jet lag * E: fatigue *<n><n><n><n>## Input<n>Input: The carpet manufacturer is using a new machine that produces the same quality with far lesser resources than a carpet it currently produces. How much time is saved using this new machine?<n><n>Rationales: The same quality with lesser resources means fewer resources.<n>Therefore, when the carpet manufacturer uses this new machine, it produces a carpet with lesser resources.<n>To solve, we first need to know how many resources are used to produce the carpet with the same quality using the old machine.<n>1. The old machine: Carpets in unit quantity that takes the previous amount of resources (i.e. quantity with resources)<n>2. New machine: Carpets that takes far lesser resources.<n><n>1. Therefore, we can conclude that old machine = unit quantity, whereas new machine = far lesser resource.<n>2. If the old machine takes resources amount ‘r‘ to produce carpets of unit quantity, then we can say the old machine = resources amount ‘r‘.<n>3. And, if the new machine takes far lesser resources amount ‘r,’ then the new machine = far less units ‘f‘.<n><n>4. When the ‘r’ and ‘f’ are compared, we can conclude that the far lesser resources amount is a lot less than the previous.<n>5. Therefore, when the carpet is produced with the resources difference of ‘r-f,’ we can conclude that the time saved with the use of the new machine is equal to ‘r-f’.<n><n><n>#### 30000<n>The Carpet manufacturer saves 3000 units of unit resources.<n><n><n><n>Answer: * The carpet manufacturer saves 12.5 hours with the use of the machine.<n><n>## Input<n>Instructions:Write a response that accurately completes the request:<n><n>Answer the following multiple choice questions, each correct response may be used

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:The man took 3 hours every morning for grooming, what is the likely result with his job? Choices:  A: tardiness B: looking good C: injury D: vacation E: neatness<n><n>### Response:		B<n><n>### Demostration:<n>Input: The man took 3 hours of grooming, what is likely result in his job?<n>Rationales<n>The meaning of the first option: _A_ stands for 'tardiness' since 'tardiness' means an early arrival and late departure at work. When a workplace is strict about the time, taking 3 hours to groom may lead to a time problem.<n>The meaning of the second option: _B_ stands for 'looking good' since 'looking good' means having a good figure. There is nothing specifically wrong with taking 3 hours of groom per day, there is just more time spent on that activity instead of doing actual work.<n>The meaning of two of the last option: _C_ stands for 'injury' since it says he will 'injure himself'. It may be a bit too rough to work out.<n>The meaning of _D_ stands for 'vacation' since workplace may have a strict policy on vacation time.<n>The meaning of last option: _E_ stands for 'neatness' since it may be 'neatness' the man is looking after all.<n>Therefore, B stands for 'looking good'.<n><n>### Answer:B Answer:

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:An attempt to confirm an applicant's reference would fail if the reference does what? Choices:  A: question B: dispute C: deny D: contradict E: refuse<n><n>### Response:		Deny<n><n>### Discuss:<n><n>

Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where is a telephone booth likely to be red? Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What is someone unintentionally hurting someone else but unable to stop likely to feel? Choices: <n>A: reinforcement, B: punishment, C: trick, D: repetition<n><n>### Response:(Reinforcement)<n><n>### Question;In basic training, what's the most frequent command? Choices:<n>A: here, B: sit, C: quiet, D: get down<n><n>### Response;A<n><n>### Coding practice<n>### Given<n><n>import java.util<n><n>String array = ["sit", "quiet", "stay"];<n><n>### Task; <n>    import java.util;<n><n>    public class test {<n><n>        public static void main(String args[]) {<n>            int j = 0;<n>            for (String s : array) {<n>                if (j == 2) {<n>                    return;<n>                }<n>                j++;<n>                System.out.println(s);<n>            }<n>        }<n>    }<n><n>### Explanation<n><n>The given data type String allows for a multitude of characters to be added to an array. <n>Those characters can be easily accessed with the usage of the for loop.<n>As it can be seen in the above program the for loop will take two parameters: "String s" and the variable "j". This variable is to be defined at beginning of the program by using 'j=0'.<n>Then a condition is applied within the for loop. It states that the condition will be true if the variable "j" takes a value of 2. That's why the for loop evaluates to false because "j" takes a default value of 0. However when the condition is reached "j" will be set to 2 and the loop will break thus returning the program.<n>Therefore in order for the program to be completed and for the output to be displayed the if statement should be in the "else if" condition rather than in the "if" condition.<n><n>### Question<n><n>Input: <n><n>### Response<n><n>### Question <n>Input: <n>### Response:<n><n>
Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where would you stand in a line and need a coat if it is cold? Choices:  A: graph B: bank at noon C: good book D: post office E: bus stop<n><n>### Response:		Choice D<n><n>### Demostration:<p>If you stand in line at the post office, you usually end up with a book under your arm. <p>When a dog is outside, he or she wants to take cover from the wind<p><n><n>### Answer: Answer: D<n><n>### Input<n>A turtle moves at half the speed of a horse. Choices:  A: driving B: road C: getting tired D: accidents E: ticket<n><n>### Response:		B<n>```<n>    Moving cars entail driving.<n>```<n>-  A: driving<n>```<n>    driving is moving cars<n>```<n>-  B: road<n>```<n>    road is moving cars<n>``` <n><n>### Input : A family of five purchased a 21-foot boat at a boating supply store. Boat seats four people, and there is 8 feet of space between each chair. Two adults and one child take a ride each day for one month. How many times did the boat get used?<n><n>### Response : A<n>```<n>    A: The boat got used 33 times<n>```<n>```<n>    2 adults plus 1 child times 10 rides<n>```<n>```<n>    A family of five is 5 people.<n>```<n>```<n><n>It just looks like their calculations:<n>```<n>    2+1*10=<<2+1*1+8>>2+1+8=29 total trips in one month<n>    5 persons times 29=<<5*29>>145 total trips made<n>```<n>### Demonstetion; What is the sum of 5 times 8 and twice negative 6?<n><n>### Correct<n>```<n>    5*8=<<5*8>>40 (sum up)<n>    twice negative 6=<<2*(negative 6)>>-12<n>    twice negative 12-(plus sign)=<<(-12)+(-12)>>24 total<n>```<n>Notice that each subtraction has a negative sign next to it which cancels out, thus when you take the sum of 5 * 8 and double negative, it automatically sums up.<n><n>
Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where would you find a binder containing homework assignments? Choices:  A: backpack B: bookcase C: office supply store D: office E: class room<n><n>### Response:		<n>The correct choice is D<n><n>### The choice that correctly completes the request is<n><n>

Choices:  A: ignore B: write C: learn new things D: illiterate E: having fun<n><n>### Response:		<n>Which Choice?<n><n>A, B, C, D, or E?<n><n>### Rationale:<n>For each multiple choice question, we will use the rule and choose the correct answer.<n><n>For each question, we must determine the correct answer.<n>For each question, if we have 5 or more options or choices, then the correct answer must not be one option or choice.<n>Therefore, we must ask ourselves, which answer does not appear or belong, in other words, the answer that does not fit and is not correct.<n><n>The first way to deal with such a question is to make all your choices correct or answerable and choose which choice does not suit your situation.<n><n>Then we will choose the one that does not suit our situation.<n><n>We can go on to eliminate multiple-choice answers that are either too small or not applicable.<n><n>To be able to eliminate answers that do not belong, we can create a situation, such as, "the correct answer is A, B, C, ____", then when we determine this situation, we can choose answers to eliminate "the correct answer is C, D, E".<n><n>Sometimes the correct answer is not B, C, D or E, so we eliminate the A, B, C and D answers, then we will eliminate all the answer answers and the correct answers are left.<n><n>####  E<n><n>Answer: E<n><n>### Test:  (Select all that apply.)<n><n>### Instructions:<n><n>Each statement is followed by four to five choices. King used the phrase "When It's Sleepy Time Down South" in his 1970 hit "Sweet Sixteen." This phrase originated in a song from 1928 sung by Blind Boy Fuller, who would sing, "When the sun goes down down South" instead of B. B. King's "sleepy." What is the best word for the meaning of "when" in this sentence? Drum and bugle corps and marching bands were commonly used in parades and festivals held for veterans, fund-raisers, and community celebrations. This means that many musicians performed in front of large crowds. With a large audience, musicians had to include lyrics that resonated with a wide variety of people and messages. <n>Because music is a form of art, many musicians made conscious decisions in their lyrics. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where in your home would you store birth control pills near your toothpaste? He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What has happened to a person's money after he or she has used the last of it? Choices:  A: dissipate B: flown C: disintegrate D: fall apart E: penultimate<n><n>### Response:		 E (penultimate)<n><n>### Explanation:<n>The word **penultimate** means last but one.  <n>After the last of the money is used, it will result in nothing, but only if the user uses all of it at once.<n><n>### A<n>**A - dissipate**<n>Dissipate means "gradually to decrease or to lose energy or momentum".<n>This would only happen if the individual takes a small amount of money and uses it before going broke.<n><n>### B<n>**B - flown**<n>Flown means "move in or as if in flight". This would imply that the money would move around before it was spending; this does not make any sense with a single individual.<n><n>### C<n>**C - disintegrate**<n>Disintegrate means "decompose into simpler substances".<n>Money does not disintegrate into simpler substances; it decomposes like a natural resource.<n><n>### D<n>**D - fall apart**<n>To fall apart means "to break or separate into pieces or into discrete parts with unmistakable identities."<n>Money does not do this, and does not even physically fall apart. It can't. It is not organic.<n><n>### E<n>**E - penultimate**<n>It is the only answer that is in the right category (`E - penultimate`) and that actually makes sense.<n><n>### F<n>**F - not given**<n><n>### Test your understanding:<n>What has happened to a persons money after he/she has used the last of its?<n><n>  Choices:  A)dissipate B)flown C)disintegrate D)fall apart E)penultimate<n><n>  ------><n><n>  # Correct<n><n>  A) Penultimate<n><n>  ## Correct<n><n><n><n>

Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where would you see a performer at a gathering of you friends? Choices:  A: bad feelings B: confusion C: going to court D: hurt feelings E: sandwiches<n><n>### Response:		A: Bad feelings<n><n>### Reason: The word civil in this case means "of or regarding lawsuits between citizens" - This is referring to legal action, as opposed to criminal action taken by the state against a criminal. If there is no consequence for a crime, people tend not to feel bad when committing it because no remedy is available.  <n>
Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What happens to people when they do not have enough food? If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What does someone chatting with friends do when they hear a joke? Answer in dollars:<n><n>Monday: ___<n>Tuesday: ___<n>Wednesday: ___<n><n>Rationale:<n>Heidi will make money as long as she sells at least 314 books for $4.40 per book.<n>The number of books sold, in any day, which has a range in which the number of books sold is 86-241, she will make the same amount of money.<n>The lowest amount of money she will make is the lowest number that she will sell if she wants to hit 314 books, which is 241.<n><n>### Source:<n>Glossary of Business Terms, [Merriam-Webster](https://www.merrim-webster.com)<n>[https://www.meram-webster.exam](https://www.Merriam-Webstet.com)<n>

Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Eating breakfast with a large family leads to a pile of what in the sink? There was a three inch difference between the longest-lasting storm and the shortest one. What was the difference in the amount of rain between the shortest and longest storm? A. Two inches B. Three inches C. Four inches D. Five inches <n>Rationales: Rain fell for three hours in the shortest-lasting thunderstorm.<n><n>For six hours the rain fell in the longest- lasting thunderstorm<n><n>The rain that fell in each thunderstorm was doubled during its lifetime.<n>If the amount of rain in the shortest- lasting thunder storm was x, it must have fallen during three times x.<n><n>If the amount of time the rain fell was x, it must be half the lifespan of the thunderstorm<n>This gives: <n><n>(x*x*3=twelve)<n><n>We solve by solving for x:<n><n>twelve/3 = 4<n><n>So the amount of rain that fell in the shortest thunderstorm was 4 inches.<n><n>Now, if we were to let x again be the amount of time the longest thunderstorm rained and y the amount of rain that fallen during its lifetime, we get:<n><n>(x*y = 6)<n><n>solving for x, <n><n>We get:<n><n>6/y = x<n><n>so:<n><n>y = 6/x<n><n>Now: <n><n>y = 2/2<n><n>y = 1<n><n>we get the lifespan of each thunderstorm:<n><n>The shortest thunderstoms lasted for three hours.  <n>The longest thunderstorms lasted for six hours.<n><n>We got:<n><n>6/1 = x<n><n>so x = 6<n><n>Therefore, rain fell for six hours in the longest thunderstrom

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:The fact the two sides were able to even reach tentative agreement was a feat to what? Choices:  A: accomplish B: make progress C: stop arguing D: do business E: concert<n><n>### Response:		E: concert<n><n>Response: E: concert<n>

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What would a person do to help someone that is not able to speak coherently? However, in a situation like this, other options would be good to help.<n>The choice for Answer is (E).<n>#<n><input type="checkbox"><n>### Input: What is a number that is used to represent a group of numbers? If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. Then it increased by \$0.25  for three weeks. And finally, it increased again by \$0.50  for two additional weeks.  Write an expression for the price of a banana. (Your answer should be in the form  p(x) where "p" is the function that represents the  price of a banana and "x" is the number of weeks since the first sale.  The expression should include all the cost increases.)  Example:   p0=2.50  p1=2.75  p2=3      Solution:  Let the number of weeks since<n><n>### Rationale<n><n>This question is quite specific. I could answer it in more than one way but I am going to go with the method most often presented in the course.<n><n>There are three different formulas for the price of a given item or service in an equation like this. This question requires an equation with the number of weeks included not only in the rate of change, the absolute value of the change, or in the original cost. In this situation, you will include only the number of weeks in the formula.<n><n>The second question is about whether someone should urinate. Urinating is a sign of fear.<n><n>#### 54 (The Price of Bananas, P2.50 for Two Weeks, and then P0.50 for Two Additional Weeks)<n><n>We would add the original cost and any rate of change at the same denominator:<n><n>$$p(x)=2\times2.50+3/2.50=5+\sqrt(3)$$<n><n>You can do the same thing with the rate of change or with the absolute value of the rate of change:<n><n>$$\sqrt(5.25)=7$$<n><n>You would not expect to do a rate of change calculation without a rate of change or an absolute value.<n><n>In this problem, you use the denominator, which is the number of weeks, not the number of total dollars or the number of total bansanas.<n><n>### Input<n>Question:You can do something like this if you give a dog a cookie. What is the oldest heat source on Earth? Choices:  A: fire B: solar energy C: sun D: house E: coal or wood<n><n>### Response:		<n><n>I chose the second choice, but there can also be other choices, such as wind.<n>If Dan decided to run on the "sun" heat source, it would be a little costly but it would also bring a lot of benefits. The sun’s energy is free and does not consume any fuels that would cost more eventually. By using the sun, we would help reduce the emissions and help our Earth, clean it. But, on the other side, if the weather is cloudy, that means less light and less heat coming in, so the heat would drop. The problem is that it is not a stable source of energy, that is why we don’t go by that option. But, there’s also the wood, coal and other heat sources that are not considered as renewable and they release carbon monoxide, they are more polluting, but they are more stable than the sun. A final choice for Dan would be the wind. The wind is a renewable energy that does not go out, its not a burning material or something, it’s like a breeze and it can stay forever if we are able to use it.<n><n><n>### Demand : How much would a person want to pay for a certain good if there was no such alternatives to that good.<n><n>### Supply: How much would it cost to produce a certain good.<n>The demand curve is the upward slope that shows the quantity demanded to the price.<n>If the price increases, it would make the quantity demanded decline, but the shape of the curve would be the same still and the price increase would continue to happen.<n>The law of supply is the other curve that describes the relationship between the quantity supplied and the price. The price increase would continue to stay the same, but the quantity supplied would be higher.<n>The relationship is upward sloping, which means that if the supply goes up, so would the price as demand goes down.<n>The same thing happens the other way around, if the supply is higher, the price would grow and demand would grow also.

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Though he was an adult he still stereotypical slept on a sofa bed in his parent's what Choices:  A: garage B: horseradish C: living room D: guest room E: basement<n><n>### Response:

Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:If a person does something to hurt someone else, they might do what? If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:If clothes have developed a smell and can't be washed what should you do with them? Choices:  A: hang in closet B: sniff C: get dirty D: become soiled E: air out<n><n>### Response:		<n>```<n>Answer: B<n>```<n>

This statement can be simplified to say the man was one row away, as one square is “n” rows by “m”cols, and “n” divides by “m”. In this case, n=3. We can then simplify this statement further to say the man was two rows away from the daughter. Now to the question. Firstly, we note that the question states the man is two squares away from the daughter, and is diagonally two and 1/2 squares away from his

Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What should you do if your pens aren't work? Choices:  A: ink in B: caps C: ink cartridges D: take notes E: scribble<n><n>### Response:		<n><n><n>### Demonsrate:<n><n><n><n>### Rationale:<n><n>><n><n><n>### 2019-06-23_at_8:27:35 AM<n>><n>  A: ink<n>  B: caps<n>  C: ink cartridge<n>  D: take notes<n>  E: scribble

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Google Maps and other highway and street GPS services have replaced what? Choices:  A: united states B: mexico C: countryside D: atlas E: oceans<n><n>### Response:		<n><n>#### A<n>Answer: A<n><n>### Credits<n>[Coursera](https://www.coursera.org/course/focv)<n>

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Mark's semen was very thick, but after his vasectomy it was also what?
