He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where could a fungus grow and not be disturbed by sunlight? Choices:  A: under rocks B: manhattan C: toenails D: grocery store E: fallen tree<n><n>### Response:		Under rocks<n><n>### Justification: Under manhattan no sunlight<n><n>### Justified: Because no sunlight<n><n>Incorrect Examples:<n><n>### Instructions:Answer the following multiple Choice question.<n><n>## Instructions:Read the questions or set of instructions carefully. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What is someone who gets angry after getting drunk likely to participate in? If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:WHat do cats get into when they are ripping things apart? If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Sam went to Paris where he ordered a blowfish at a sushi place. A: launch pad B : circus C: aircraft carriers, D (for large open areas) and E: Space station<n>```ruby<n>def mobile_launched_platform?(input)<n>  if input.blank?<n>    raise ArgumentError.new("You cannot leave argument blank.")<n>  end<n><n>  if input == "E"<n>    puts "Correct."<n>    return "E. Space Station is a mobile launching pad!"<n>  elsif input == "C"<n>    puts "Eligible!"<n>    return "C. Aircraft Carrier is a mobile launching paddle!"<n>  elsif (input == "B" || input == "C")<n>     puts "Ineligible!"<n>     return "Mobile Platforms such as Aircraft Carriers can not be launched off the ground since they are mobile!"<n>  elsif input.to_uppercase == "P"<n>    puts "Ineligable!"<n>    return "The mobile platform you gave is not a mobile platform, but a carrier! mobile platforms are capable of being mobile, where carriers cant."<n>  else<n>    raise ArgumentError, "Please give valid input. The input was #{input.inspect}."<n>  end<n>end<n>```<n><n><n>Answer: If you choose to run this code through a method, it should give you the result you are expecting, as long your choices are "space station," "aircraft carrier," "circus," "large open area" and "launch pad"

Choices:  A: see work B: practice C: quiz D: school grade E: homework<n><n>### Response:		 If you did well on the tests, you might get an _A, practice quiz_ as what? see work school grade homework<n>### Justification:  If you did the well on the test, it is likely that you earned and A as a grade which is the first option. Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where is a fox likely to be caught? If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:When people discover something new while chatting with friends, why are they likely to continue talking? Choices:  A: agreement B: to fill their time C: discomfort D: misunderstanding E: learning about<n><n>### Response:		I believe D is the right answer because they are more likely to learn about the things they are talking about<n><n>### Input:"Increasing your daily step count is good for your heart," says the ad. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Janet knew she was dying from her injuries because she could feel herself doing what? Do not calculate the discount.<n><n>## Input<n>```<n>- 75 50 49<n>```<n><n>## Rationales<n>```<n>- 40% of 82.5 = <<40% of 0.825=31.5>>31.5<n>- Half of the total cost would be (31.5 + 50)+49 = 90.5<n>```<n><n>## Output<n>```<n>90.5<n><n>```<n>## Instruction<n>If a student sells a book for 3 times the cost and a game for twice the cost, how much does she make at the game and the book fair?<n><n>##
Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:He was a very sharp engineer, but when it came to the details his calculations could were often what? Choices:  A: complimentary B: inelegant C: ocean D: dull E: inaccurate<n><n>### Response:		A:Complimentary<n><n><n>### Input :How many times must you factor to make the number between 1 and 1000 that has the fewest factors?<n>### Answer : 6<n>### Rationale<n>1+2+3+4+5=15<n>1+2+5=16<n>1+2+7=18<n>1+3+6=19<n>1+4+8=20<n>1+5+10=25<n>1+7=8<n>1+1+2=4<n>1+1+3+4=10<n>1+1+1+2+3=7<n>1+1+4+6=10<n>19*1=19<n><n>### Input  : Which is larger, 1,012,345 or 6,255,513?<n>### Answer :6,255<n>### Rationale:6255+55+13=255<n>## Input : 47=A<n>84=B<n><n>### Answer : D<n>### Rationale :47+84=131<n>##Input : What is the first two digits of 1907<n>### Answer :91<n>### Rationale  : 97 + 18 = 115<n>##Input : 54+7= A<n>48<n>### Rationale A is the only pair where the sum of the digits is 3<n>##Input : 68+19 = B<n>37

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:To properly instruct children attending school you would need a great deal of what? Which leaves 280 - (1 hr + 28 mph*hr) = 269 mph.<n>This can be approximated as 269(1) = 268.9 hrs<n>#### 5 hours<n>Answer: 5 hours<n><n>### Inputs: A dog is kept in

Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Sometimes it felt like being able to pay bills was the only reason he was actively what? Making money: He didn't have money when he was being active, so he felt that his reason for activity was to make money.<n>E. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where would you go if you didn't feel like baking a cake yourself? How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:The parents thought their children should learn teamwork, what were they signed up for? Choices:  A: throw things B: play sports C: play games D: play ball E: play chess<n><n>### Response:		Choices: A: throw things, B: play sports, C: play games, D: play ball, Answer: B (play sports)<n><n>### Input #2:Two boys play each other in a game of baseball for a total of 9 innings. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What would release energy, but not mainly in your muscles? Choices:  A: vent B: think C: shouting D: work off E: exercise<n><n>### Response:		<n>Let me first tell you about the word energy; Energy is the work done on a system, or the quantity of work done on a system or the capacity for work in a given time. Energy may exist in two forms: (a) potential energy and (b) kinetic energy.<n><n>**Work** is also defined as the process in which, one object's forces are applied from another object, such that the first object's motion is changed. In other words, for objects moving to different locations, and forces acting, one or more, or many of the forces can be considered as work.<n><n>> The only energy needed for us to exercise is within us, not from the surroundings, and we use that energy to exercise.<n>Let's see how energy is lost during exercise, and the energy obtained from exercise.<n><n>1) **Energy lost during exercises**: During the exercise, we may sweat with the help of perspiration gland. When sweat comes out, it contains water, salts, lactate(acetic acid) and urea(carbon, hydrogen and nitrogen). Here only one part of energy is lost, the water(as weight lost) and energy(as sweat loss), and the rest of the energy are not lost, instead, the energy is required to maintain our internal functions such as blood circulation, breathing, digestion, and the muscles activity. This energy is recovered in the same way, it is through external source, from the air (as oxygen), food (as glycogen in the blood and liver).<n>2) **Energy obtained from exercise**: In our activities, some energy is obtained from the surrounding environment. When we breathe, we move air in and out. The process in which gas(usually air) is moved in or out of lungs is known as respiration. Let me tell you what the process involves and its result:<n><n>Respiration is a combination of two processes or reactions. First, inhalation: When we breathe in, air moves into the lungs, which are large, balloon-like structures in our chest cavity. Air moves into the lungs through one or both nostrils, mouth or an opening in the throat.<n><n>Second, is exhalation: When we exhale, the air leaves the lungs

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. Choices: A: awake B: asleep C: alert D: aware E: open eyes<n><n>### Demostration:<n>Input: Someone who is awake may or may not know what's going<n>Rationales: Conscious refers to "having or showing awareness of one's own existence and of things around one". While this may refer to whether or not an individual can respond to an external action or event, it also refers to what an individual thinks about these events or things. For example, if an individual notices an earthquake, they may be not be aware of their existence (i.e. not respond) because they are in deep sleep; however, if someone who is awake is able to respond and notice the earthquake's existence, they have gained conscious of the event. While open eyes refers to the ability to physically see, awareness is more related to noticing. Hence, someone who is awake refers to someone who has gained "conscious."<n><n>#### 2<n>Answer: A<n><n>Input: Write a sentence with an independent clause and then a dependent clause. Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What could be happening near you if the ground is getting wet? A lazy cat<n>Rationales: C = C<n>D = Mean<n>E = I will not continue<n><n>#### C<n>Answer: C<n><n>Input: The sun is just beginning to set. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. (use pictures)<n><n>    x in the above problem equals to: 2<n><n>    We need to show that a is greater than d<n>    a and d is x +1<n>    a = 9 + x = 9 + 2<n>    a is 9 + (2) = 0<n>    d = 3 + 2 = 5<n>    to show that the value is 9 + x > the value of 3 + x we need to show that 9 + x > 3 + x<n>    we can do this by adding 6 to both sides:<n>    (9 + x)+5 = 9(1) + 5  = 9(5) = 45<n>    (3 + 2)+(5 - 6) = 6 + (5-1) = 6+4 = 10<n>    this shows that the value of 9+x is greater than 3+

Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:If you aren't experiencing curiosity and want to ensure viewing enjoyment, what may you watch? Choices:  A: alabama B: louisiana C: south carolina D: arkansas E: mountains<n><n>### Response:		D<n><n>In coastal and gulf states: Alabama, Louisiana, South Carolina, and Alabama are coastal. However, Florida and Mississippi are not. Therefore "Louisiana" is not a correct option. " Arkansas" and "mountains" are the incorrect options as they are not either of the coastal states. Only "A," "B," and "E" represent coastal states. A is not correct. South Carolina is not a coastal state. D is incorrect. So the answer is "E" as it is the only correct response.<n><n>### The correct response is: D<n>### The correct explanation is:<n>"If one sees a foX and is stanDing in a coastal, goUl state, where is this perSon?" Choices: "A" alAbama, "B" louisiana, "C" south carolina, "D" arkansas, "E" mountaIns."<n><n>### Input:"A"<n><n>### Response:"D"<n><n>In coastal states: Although "A" sounds good, the capital of Alabama is Montgomery and it is inland. Therefore, Alabama is not a coastal or gulf state.<n>Louisiana is a coastal state but it is not gulf. In fact, it is the only state that touches the Gulf of Mexico and the Mississippi River.<n>South Carolina is an inland state that borders Georgia. It has Charleston, which is the largest city.<n>Arkansas is an inland state and is bordered by seven other states. It does not border the gulf or any other seashores.<n>Although it states that Florida and Mississippi are coastal, it is incorrect. Both states are coastal or gulf.<n>E is the only correct choice. The only inland state is Arkansas, not E. The only gulf states are Alabama, Louisiana and South Carolina, not E. Therefore, E is correct.<n><n>### Input"B"<n><n>### The incorrect response was: A.<n>### The correct rationale was: Although "A" seems to make sense given the fact a fox and a person could be located in Alabama, the capital of Alabama, Montgomery, is inland. Therefore Alabama is not a coast or a gulf state.<n>### Correction :The response:"Correct Response

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where might a yard be tiny? Choices:  A: farmland B: neighborhood C: city D: property E: subdivision<n><n>### Response:		<n><n>### Demand:<n>Input: In a survey, 89% of respondents thought the cottage industry was doing poorly. If the cottage industry's revenue last year was $36,000, what was the revenue in 2017?<n>Rationales What are the given information tells you?<n>Given: In the survey 89% of the responders think the cottage industry is poorly performing.<n>89% of responders think the cash cottage is poorly performed, so 11% of responders think cottage industry is well performing.<n>Given Cottage industry's income in 2016 is $36,0<n>If the cash cash industrial income is poorly performed but 11 % of respondents think this industry is well performing industry, we can increase the income by 11%.<n>#### 11%<n>Reward:<n>#### 36060<n>Answer: 39920<n><n>### Demostration:<n><n>### Input<n>Input: A bird rests on a branch for 2 seconds and flies for 8 seconds in continuous trips. After 16 trips, a large predator chases it away; in what ratio is the number of trips to the length of time it stays on the branch and in flight in that 16th trip?<n>Rationales<n>Input: A bird will rest on the branch for (8-2)/24 = <<8-2/24=1/3>>1/3 seconds<n>After 16 trips on the branch, the predator come along and it chase the bird away. <n>#### 1/3<n>Reward:The ratio of the numbers of trips to the time it remain is 16 to 1 = 1 to 16/1

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:When I was home, I was comfortable.  But I had a crippling fear of going where? Choices:  A: outside B: vacation C: idle D: apartment E: neighborhood<n><n>### Response:		 The correct answer is outside.  The second sentence describes the author before leaving home but without identifying where he was.  The author's "crippling fear of" somewhere outside his home is also emphasized earlier, in the first sentence.<n><n>### Input 1: Which describes how A. B. and C. compare? Choices: A: they are similar B: they are different C: They are equal D: They can be easily compared<n><n>### Response 1: The choices don't really "describe how" A, B and C compare.  That idea is never expressed.<n><n>###  Response 2: The answer is in the first choice,  where the phrase "easily compared" appears.<n><n><n>### Inputs<n><n>1. Describe how you know the following people. <n><n>   - Jack is tall.<n>   - Ida has brown eyes.<n>   - Mary has long hair.<n>2. Match the descriptions with the correct person.<n>   - Jack is very careful.<n>   - Mary is neat.<n>   - I am very tidy.<n><n>### Response<n>1.  We know they are all people because the question uses the word people.  Each person in turn is given a characteristic (described in the first sentence).  Then we are told whether those characteristics fit the named people, who are listed in the choices.  If the characteristic is true of the person, we choose yes.  <n>2.  The correct choices are left to right.<n><n>### Description<n><n>#### Topic<n><n>What does a sentence need in order to be complete?<n><n>In these questions, you will select a sentence that is incomplete or lacking information.  Each option describes an addition that could make the sentence complete.<n><n>> #### Tip<n>> Remember that the addition needs to address the grammatical _content_ of the sentence.  Sometimes you will find only one correct way of adding the information.  On other occasions you will have several possible options.  In those cases, carefully read the question to identify what is missing from the sentence.  Be sure to pay close attention to the words used in the original sentence.<n>><n><n>#### Instruction <n>- Review the question carefully.  Identify exactly what is missing from the incomplete sentence.<n>- Choose a selection that accurately fills in the missing information.  If

He made 18 of a specific type of line, 12 of another type of line, 7 of a final type of line, 4 of yet another type of line, and 3 of a final type. There were a total of 43 patterns made. How many types of patterns can there be?<n><n>### answer<n><n>Answer: 6. The total of each type of pattern would have to add up to 43, so we subtract 43 all together. We can say that the patterns cannot be more than 43. We need to figure out how many patterns there can be with 43 being more than or equal to any number of types of pattern.<n><n>Answer: 3<n><n>### Solution<n>For an input with less than 40 types, we'll solve by doing a simple algorithm:<n><n>1) Start with a large array A[i] for i=0..43<n><n>2) Set i=0<n><n>3) i=i+1.<n><n>4) If i==A[i], goto 1<n><n>5) If a[i]!=A[i], then A[i] is used, put 1 in A[i]<n><n>6) Return A[i], the number of patterns<n><n><n>![enter image description here](https://i.post

Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where is a system of electronic devices likely to be used in school? Choices:  A: nature B: toilet C: computer science D: computer store E: human body<n><n>### Response:		<n>Toilet, because it's the only place you can be alone in school besides in your head. <n>It also involves your mind, your body, and your future.<n><n>### Input::What is the value of a + b + c + d + e + f + 15? Choices: 1. b 	2. a + e 	3. 0	4. 58	5. c<n><n>### Response::<n>3<n><n>### Input : The product of 5 and the quotient of 8 and 8 is 40. What is the missing number? Choice A) 5<n>Choice B) 2<n>Choice C) 4<n>Choice D) 8<n>Choice E) 80<n><n>### Response :<n>a)2<n>b)4<n>c)5<n>d)8<n>e)80<n><n>Input : 10 + 30 + 33 + 6 + 89 =258 Output : 10 + (30 + 3.14) =2.14 + (33 + 6) =2.19 + (89 + 83) =562.19 + 571  =593.149 + 83 =676Input: The number of times it rains in October<n>is the same as the number of times it does NOT rain in March. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. Choices:  A: auditioning B: hear sounds C: listening to music D: making music E: arthritis<n><n>### Response:		<n><n>### If someone is playing guitar, then we say that they are performing. Another word for performing a skill is auditioning. In this way, a person can audition for a musical program or group, or for an instrumental ensemble such as a string or brass quartet. We can also call the performance a listening to music or a music lesson, and we can even call it a making music session, referring to improvisation or a jam session. So this question is about whether the performer is auditioning, trying to listen to music, or making music. A person doesn't have arthritis of the hands to play guitar.<n><n>#### None of the given choices answer the question.<n><n>#### 1(A):A:<n>Answer: A<n><n>### What is the difference between a bird's eye view and at eye level? If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What does a chicken do in a joke? If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:A projector displayed people on the huge screen while the audience laughed. Choices:  A: persuade B: slept C: take center stage D: challenge E: speak clearly<n><n>### Response:		The lady was doing a one-man-show of her tell-a-story, When the show began she ________. The response can’t be "persuade," because the lady was giving her own play instead of persuading or convincing others to listen or see the show. The response can’t also be “sleep,” because that would imply that she was doing something wrong, and the question itself does not describe something wrong with what she did. The response can’ t be “challenge,” because the question doesn’ t describe she challenge anyone, she just started. The response couldn’t also be “take center stage,” because that would imply she was doing something wrong and she wouldn’t challenge everyone if she was doing something wrong. The only possible result is "speak clearly."<n><n>#### SpeakClearly<n><n>You're correct. The lady was speaking clearly when she started her play.<n><n>#### SpeakClarly<n><n>Answer: speak clearly<n><n>#### Speakclarly<n><n>You've correctly provided the response.<n><n>#### SpeAKclar<n><n>Good job. Your response is correct.<n><n>### Input:"The farmers of the land were busy planting corn." When the book was written, what part of speech is "the farmers of the land"? Choices: A. Adjective B. Adverb C. Interjection D. Prepositional Phrase E. Noun<n><n>### Response:"The farmers of " _________ " were busy planting corn" When the book was written the main idea of the sentence is the adjective word "the." You can take out “The farmers." From that, you can see that the adjective word “of the land” should be before the noun “land” since the adjective describes what the land is like. “Farmers " is just a group of people that are working at the same time to do something to help the land grow. So the correct response is “Adjective.”<n><n>#### ADjective<n><n>You've provided the correct answer!<n><n>#### ADjective1<n><n>Good job.<n><n>#### Noun<n><n>I got this answer right<n><n>### Input"The lady's father, an engineer, was driving too fast.” When the sentence was written, the comma in "The lady's father" was placed _________<n><n>Choices: A. after a coordinating conj
Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where would you store a shopping bag if all the seats in your vehicle are full? After finding x, x can be substituted for in the original equation.<n><n>#### 11 - x - 6 - w = 0<n>The coefficient of x is 1 as it is a constant. <n>We can use the remainder theorem as follows:<n>11 - x - (6 + w) = 11 - x = 6 + w<n>We can find the value of x from the above equation:<n>6 + w = 6 + w = x<n>We can substitute x for in the above equation:<n>11 - w + w = 19<n>We can solve the above equation by using the substitution method:<n>w = 2 or w = -2<n>x + 6 + w can be evaluated as 6,6 - 2 or 6, 6+2<n><n>Let, w=2<n><n>The answer would be x=6<n><n>Let, w=-2<n><n>The answer to the question would be x=-6<n><n>Answer: 6 or -6<n><n>### Next Step<n>In order to evaluate polynomial by using two variables method, we have to evaluate the polynomial by substituting the values of one or two variables in the equation. Then we can replace the given value in the equation. The next step would require us to compute and substitute the values of x and w to the original equation.<n>#### 6 + 6w - 11 = 0<n>The

Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:James was cooking s stew in his apartment kitchen. How many centimeters of the stitches of the board was less than the 27,000 centimeters of the  stitches of the  onion?<n>Rationales The cutting board was (4911)(2/1) = <<4911*2/1=9822>>9822 stitches long.<n>The cutting board was less than the onion by (4911-27618) = <<49822-(27618)->>47216 stitches long<n>The number of centimeters (cm) in 9,822 cm =<<9822cm=9,822>>9,822<n>There was a difference of 47,216 x 9,82 cm = <<47216*982=470856>>470857 cm remaining of the stitches which were less than the onion.<n>Since there were 98,220 stitches, there were 1,528 cm remaining.<n>Therefore, 1,529 cm was less than the 49,111 cm of the onion.<n>#### 1529<n>Answer: 1529 Centimeters<n><n>### Input::Write a response that appropriately complete the request. <n><n>### Demos:

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. Choices:  A: problems B: not noticeable C: deflation D: economic instability E: eat cake<n><n>### Response:		E: eat cake.<n><n>### Rationales:Deflation:<n>A decrease in the overall price level. It may be caused by a decline in aggregate demand (a decrease in money demand). A decrease in the overall price that has occurred for an extended period is referred to as debasement.<n>Fundamental reasons for the deflation of prices include the following:<n><n>1. a decrease in the money supply<n>2. decreased demand and/or slower growth in overall demand<n><n>When the money supply is reduced, the overall price level falls, resulting in a state of deflation. Deflation might also happen if the overall demand for products decreases, causing a decrease in the economy's overall growth rate.<n>Demand-Pull Deflation<n>Aggregate demand is often defined as the total demand for products and services in the economy, as well as the aggregate value of the demand in the entire economy.<n>Aggregate demand can be divided into consumption, investment, government, and net exports. In an economy, the greater the overall demand for products and services, the higher the aggregate demand, which implies that prices are rising and the reverse is also true.<n>Demand Deflation:<n>When there is a decrease in overall demand in the economy, demand deflation occurs. This type of deflation is caused by a drop in the demand in businesses. When there is a decline in demand for goods and services, the economy's demand will fall, and consequently the economy's supply of products and services.<n><n>### Output 2:<n><n>### Demand:<n><n>### Supply:<n><n>A supply curve is a graphical representation that shows the amount of a product that suppliers are willing to offer for a given price, and over a particular period of time. Producers would offer more of their commodity at a given price in the following graph.<n>A downward-sloping supply curve means that suppliers are ready to sell more at lower prices and vice-versa. A supply curve's shape does not, in fact, reflect the quantity of goods that producers intend to sell. On the contrary, it shows how much they are prepared to provide.<n><n>A supply curve's horizontal shape indicates that the suppliers are willing to sell the same quantity of goods for any given price. This form of supply curve is known as "a supply of

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:We do not have rest, so how are we feeling? Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:The kids had been having fun all day, there was now a what? If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where did the compassionate farmer allow the heifer to reside during her last days? Choices:  A: cattle ranch B: countryside C: grocery store D: slaughterhouse E: dairy farm<n><n>### Response:		If we are talking about a cow then the answer will be E: dairy farm or else the answer will be B: countrysides<n># Challenge4<n>### Solution1<n># Input: How many marbles could you trade in for all the others if you had only 27 in your collection? Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What could someone be doing while performing that cannot be enjoyed by deaf people? How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where should an excavation never take place? Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Reaching advantage position in a competitin puts me in what position as compared to others? Choices:  A: determination B: upper hand C: superior D: higher position E: skill<n><n>### Response:		E<n><n>### Input2:<n>How many square tiles are there on the floor of the library? Choices:  -5 A: 5 B: 4 C: 7 D: 3 E: 6<n><n>### Response2:<n>5 is correct<n><n>### Input3:<n>Anthony’s father asks him to draw a graph to show how much money he will spend in different categories. Anthony decides to make each category a dot on the graph. How many dots should he place on the graph? Choices:  +3 A: 5 B C: 3 D: 4 E: 7<n><n>### Response3:<n>4 is correct<n><n>## <n>

The underlined sentence should read: People always spoke childishly to him, even though he couldn't walk.<n><n>### Examples:1. He fell off a diving board at the swimming pool when he was six years old. The swimming pool was empty and no one saw it happen. Choices:  A. There were eight people there B. The water was deep C. The other children didn't like him D. The water was shallow E. Everybody was in the shower<n><n>### Example Outcome:B<n><n>### Except:Everyone was showering. No one saw that he fell. That's why he thought it was safe to dive and why they never saw him fall. However, even with the pool empty, the water was not shallow.  The water was deep enough for him to dive and be injured. So, when no one stopped him from diving, the swimming pool was deep enough for him. Therefore, Choice B is False.<n><n>Answer: D. Everybody was in shower <n><n>### Reference: 2013, Kaplan Test Prep CPSAT<n>
