If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:The swimming pool couln't be refilled due to drought regulations, where was it located? But, due to improper punctuation mark (,) <n>the right answer was misplaced as the other way around.<n>

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. Choices:  A: board ship B: grocery shop C: cross street D: feel happy E: shout at<n><n>### Response:		<n>#### A: board ship<n><n>### Rationales:<n>-  Board ship is an activity a person uses to transport goods.<n>-  The verb in the question is do.<n>-  Board ship has the verb DO used on the word board ship, the action (BOARD).<n>-  The other activities a person might do are not related to the verb DO.<n>-  Grocery shop has the verb SHOP which is not related to the verb (DO).<n>-  Cross street has the word CROSS which is not related to DO.<n>-  Feel happy is an adjective and an activity is the action you do (FEEL).<n>-  Shout at is an action verb.<n><n>### Input- The word that means “to do”:<n><n>### Rationale:<n>The word that means “to DO” is “DO”.<n>This word is also related to the meaning of the sentence in the question, since it is the DO word in the phrase “a person do something”.<n><n><n>

If each elephant is 7 feet tall, how tall is the tallest elephant after the last elephant in line?<n>Rationales:(In order) 8 feet tall, 9 feet tall, 10 feet tall and 11 feet is 11 feet.<n>11 feet tall is the last elephant. Let me call the last elephant X elephant.<n>The tallest elephant before X is 8 feet. Let me call the elephant before X elephant A.<n>I know the total of the remaining elephant height in the line, so let’s subtract the remaining elephant total from 29 (Total of the 4 elephants before X). So the total before X is 29 - X.<n>The 4 elephant before X total is 29 + 9 + 10 + 11 = 79.<n>X is 11, so the total is 79 - 11 = <<79-11=68>>68 feet tall<n><n>#### 68<n>Answer: 68<n><n>### Input<n><n>Input: There are 23 pancakes in a pan on the stove. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where could you find some airplanes that are not being used? Choices:  A: war B: aircraft carrier C: sky D: graveyard E: crash<n><n>### Response:		<n>B,C,E<n><n>### Instructions:<n>Answers all three questions.<n>### Input:<n>Input: What year will the 250th episode of a TV show air? A: After the year 2045.<n>B: During the year 2032.<n>C: Some year after 2023.<n>D: In 20 minutes.<n>E: After all the episodes have been broadcast.<n>Rationales: For A, <<250>250>>250 episodes would have to have been broadcast first.<n>For B, <<250>>2032 + 250 >>= 450 <n>The 450th episode occurs some time after 450-250 = 200 >>> 200 years. << 200=200>>200 + 450 = <<450>>450 years after that year, so <<450>>200 > 2045, which is after 2045-200 = <<2045-450>>155 years.<n>For C, the number of episodes that have been broadcast thus far <<250>>(250 + 250) = <<500>>500<n>The number of episodes left <<250>>500 - 250 = <<250>>459<n>The number of years since the first episode will also be <<500>>459 years, so 459+500 = <<459+450>>990 years from the first episode.<n>This is <<990>>990 - 459 = <<531>>531 years from the current year, so <<531>>100 years after 2031, not <<2031>>2031.<n>For D, <<250+20000>>D=<<250+40000>><<D>> D must be <<20000+250>>=<<34750>>34750.<n>D must be <<34750/12>>

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What planet is the atlantic ocean part of? Choices:  A: planet B: basin C: submarines D: earth E: pacific<n><n>### Response:		A<n>What is the correct answer? What is the logical deduction that makes the answer to this question true?<n><n>### Demystification:<n><n>Input: This is an image of the 16 regions on the Earth that are part of the Pacific Ocean. The Pacific Ocean is a gigantic ocean that holds one-third of the total water in the world. The Pacific Ocean Basin is a huge region that is approximately 113 million square miles or the size of the continental US, China, India, Russia, Brazil, South and Central America, etc. combined. The image below shows the 245 million square mile Pacific Ocean with its 16 parts. <n><n>![](images/16-parts-pacific.jpg){: width="70%" height="70%"}<n><n>Rationales:<n>To answer this question, you first need to understand what the Pacific Ocean is.<n><n>**1. Pacific Ocean**<n>The Pacific Ocean is the largest of the world's five oceans and covers almost a third of the Earth's surface. It is called the Pacific Ocean because Spanish explorers believed that they had sailed all the way from Cape Horn on the South American west coast to the Islands of the East Indies. They assumed that they had circumnavigated, or gone all the way around, the entire earth. The Spanish explorers were named "Pedro Alvares Cabrillo" and "Ferdinand Magellan" (the explores who first sailed west across the Pacific Ocean). The reason it is called the planet because it is the largest of the 5 oceans in the world and it is 3/4 (3/4) of the Earth`s surface. It is the only ocean that is larger than the entire continent of Africa.<n><br> <br> <br> **2. Atlantic Ocean**<n>The Atlantic Ocean is the second largest ocean and is also known as the Ocean of Dreams. It is the oldest of the worlds oceans and plays an important role in world trade. Europe also gets its name from the word 'atlantic' since they were a group of people that lived close to the seashores and sold their fish to travelers.<n><n><br> <hr> <br><n># 2021_10_9<n>### 답은 �

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. They prefer the bark of broad-leaved trees, but they will eat almost anything. A healthy beaver can eat more than two-thirds of its own body weight each day and can have as much as 25% of its weight in storage.<n>Beavers have 40 sharp and flattened teeth, which can cut through as much as 30 cm or 1 foot thick lumber in less than 20 minutes.<n>The beaver tail is almost a perfect ovoid or egg shape for the efficient propulsion through the water.<n>Although beavers are considered to be rodents, their tails are not connected to their urinary system and are not a natural means of communication with other beavers.<n>#### Beaver Fact 1<n><n>#### Beaver Facts 3<n><n>### Input :The first year we went to the water park, we made $2,000. If the number of days is between 4 and any number, this would have to be a Friday. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where could you find an armchair that is used by only a few people? Choices:  A: doctor's office B: hospital C: apartment D: study E: furniture store<n><n>### Response:		E<n><n>### Rationale:<n>```none<n>```<n><n>### Demostration:<n>```python<n>input = 'C'<n>print(f"A: {input.capitalize()}, B: {input.title()}, 'C: {input}')<n>```<n><n>```<n>A: Doctor's office, B: Doctor's office', C: C<n>```<n>### Answer:C <n>### Input: Which of the following is the correct sequence of steps involved in creating a Word document using Microsoft Word? Choices:  I: open up Word, A: create a title page, B: create a paragraph with text, C: save as a PDF, D: save as a Word document<n><n>### Response : B,C, A<n><n>### Rationales <n>```none<n>``` <n><n>### Démostration: <n>### input = 'B,C, A'<n>### print('I:', input.capitalize())<n>### print('A:', input.title())<n>###<n>###<n>```<n>I: B,C, A A: B, C, A<n>```<n>### Rational: The steps involved in creating a word document are input.title().upper().split()<n><n>### Input : I: create a paragraph with some text, A: add a header, B: create a table of figures, C: create an image, D: add a picture<n><n>### Response D,C,B,A<n>### Rationale :<n>Input = input.title().split() <n>```<n>1: D,C,B<n>1: [C, B, D]<n>2: I, A, B, C, D<n>2: [A, B, C, I, D]<n>```<n>### Démonstration: <n><n>    Output: D: add a link to a web page B: add the word 'the' to a certain sentence C: check for spelling errors A: write a message using plain text<n><n>### Rationals <n><n>    Input: input = D:A:B:<n><n>2: input = [D, A, B]<n>### Démosstration : <n><n>Output : D:A:B<n>```none<n>```
Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where is one likely to hear a harpsichord? Choices:  A: make noise B: band C: museum D: concert hall E: rubber band<n><n>### Response:		B<n>### Justification:Choice B is the correct answer.<n>#### Answer (Choices):B

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where would you dispose of a broken icebox? Choices:  A: antique store B: in the graveyard C: kitchen D: junk yard E: ice<n><n>### Response:		<n>D. In the junk yard<n><n>### Input<n>What is the next integer in the sequence: { 2, 1, 3, -1, -2, 0, 4, 7, -4, -7}<n><n>### Response<n><n>### Input-E<n><n>```<n>1. If the 10000 in a 10^3 is less than the 100 you are looking at, then 10^3<10.<n>2. If 10^3=100, then the 25^2=500=<100, so 10^2<10.<n>3. If 10^(i<2) are all numbers <10, then 10>10^5.<n>4. If the entire sequence above is 1) { 2, 5, 5, -9, -4, -9} or 2) { 1, 4, 4, -9, -2, -9} then 10 is the maximum number in the sequence.<n>5. This sequence is { 2, 2, 4, -2, -4, 9, -9, 5} which has 5 as the maximum number.<n>```<n>

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:We want to try some new barbecue sauces, where should we buy some? How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:The man needed to buy flooring, where was he looking for it? Choices:  A: walmart B: loft C: house D: home depot E: kitchen<n><n>### Response:		<n><n>Rationales:A walmart is a place where the man could've been looking to buy flooring.<n><n>### Input<n>:How many cats does Mrs. Clow have? If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where do you put your grapes just before checking out? How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What could happen to a paper if you leave it outside even if it does not move? Choices:  A: one material often recycled B: ripped C: saturated with water D: one dimensional E: crumpled<n><n>### Response:		I need help on this.<n><n>### The first number that is the same in a specific list is the answer.<n>

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Who was the head of the branch yelling at? Choices:  A: owner B: foot C: subordinate D: base E: point<n><n>### Response:		A<n><n>### Input:(I'm a spy) and I'm supposed to steal your password to make sure you are on duty. I will give it back to you though.<n><n>### Response:(I'm on duty)<n><n>### Input:"Yes, sir! My name is Tom. I'm on the base. There's my point (I'm the point)."<n><n>### Response:"Yes, sir! I'm working on point 27 and should be done in 12 minutes. There's my base (I'm the base)."<n><n>## Instructions:<n>* The prompt is a question asking for feedback after using a form. Choose the option A, B, C and D that provides the most helpful feedback.<n>* 5 min writing<n><n>### Instructions:Answer the following essay in your booklet. Choose one of the essays with comments to your response below.<n>Choose one of the essay responses given below. Write an introduction and conclusion for your response. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. How many degrees is it below the average temperature?<n>Rationales and Discussion:<n>I. 123 4 567 123 2 4 5 76<n>II. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:The skin was cut while chopping onions, where was this skin likely cut? Choices:  A: good health B: finger C: meat D: body E: own family<n><n>### Response:		A<n><n>### Instructions:Select the best answer that solves the problem<n><n>### Instructioin:Answer the following multiple-choice question.<n><n>## Rationales:The skin is likely cut while chopping onion.<n><n>### Cutting the skin:<n>### while the person is chopping the onion:<n>### There is a good chance that this skin will be cut:<n>The next best answer was A<n><n>### Answer:C<n><n>### Response : B<n><n>### Instrectaion:Answer the following multiplechoicequestion<n><n>### Demostration:<n>### A:good health<n>### B:finger<n>### C:meat<n>### D:body<n>### E:ownfamily<n><n>### Instrictaion:Ann has 246 pencils. Mary has five more pencils than Ann. Which of the following equations could describe this situation?<n><n>### Demstration:<n>### Options 1:<n>### 2x=1 + 2*5<n><n>M=2x<n>M=2x-1<n>x*(2x-1) = 1<n>x(2x) = (1-x)<n>2x2 = (1-x)/x<n>2x2 = 100/(2x)<n>2x = 100/2<n>4 * 2 = 4<n><n>### Options 2:<n>### Ann has 24 pencils and 20 of them are good. Mary then takes 15 good pencils away. Write an equation to describe this situation.<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>### 24=20+15<n><n>### <n>### 3*20 = 20<n><n>### Answer=24<n><n>### Answer D<n><n>### Input<n>A:good health<n>B:finger<n>C:meat<n>D:body<n>E:ownfamily<n><n>##### 20<n><n>

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:If you want to make a big splash in a river with a rock, from where should you throw it? Choices:  A: mountains countryside B: ground C: bridge D: mountain range E: surface of earth<n><n>### Response:		A. The rocks you throw in the countryside will travel furthest (i.e., will have the greatest velocity).<n><n>### Justification:When you throw the rock from the ground, it travels a short distance downward and not far forward.<n><n>### When you throw the rock from a mountain, it travels downward until the force of gravity reduces its speed. It is then accelerated by force of gravity.<n><n>### The rock travels downward in the mountains, and then travels at least a length of the river on a trajectory parallel to the ground.<n><n>### However, the rock travels the longest distance when launched into the countryside. It is launched without an initial velocity, and then gains velocity.<n><n>#### A<n>Answer:A<n><n>### Input<n>A farmer has 7 apples and 9 bananas. Five apples are bananas. In this case, what is the result?<n>A. Incorrect<n>B. 12 fruit<n>C. 17 fruit<n>D. 19 fruit<n>E. 5 fruit<n><n><n>#### B<n>Answer:B<n><n>### InputInput: Four boys need to line up behind their teacher. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:John and Jane were a couple.  They were dating for a while and wanted to be together for even longer. For this reason, they did what? Choices:  A: make sex B: plan to marry C: dance D: electrical circuit E: row about<n><n>### Response:		A<n>### Answer: A<n><n>### Input:"John" +1.5 = "Ronald" and "Jane" -1.2 = "Sharon".  Are they related?<n><n>### Rationale:<n>I'm not certain but I'm pretty sure they'r not<n><n>### InputAliens from the planet Xyno created a solar powered energy field that provides free of charge energy to their home planet for 72 minutes and 59 seconds. If the average person uses 24.15 watts per hour, how much time must pass before the people of earth make up for what they would spend on power using solar power?<n>RationalesThe average person uses 28.1 watts per hour.<n>24.15 / 28.1 = <<24.15/28.1=0.86>>0.86 hours<n>9 hours and 15 minutes<n><n>### InputWhen a person has a net worth of $15000.42, their net worth is the sum of their assets plus their liabilities.  The value of an assets changes $43.22 while the value of a liability increases by $78.56.  The value of the person's income stream increases by 4.8% during this period. If 5% of the population are immigrants to the country, what percent of the immigrants are from the country?<n>Rationales3 more than five times 30 times the the number of people from the country in a different country is 85.<n>Let the number of people from different country be X times 0.05<n>85 = 3*30*X<n><n>X = 35.375% of 5%

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. After giving each patient a toothbrush, he instructed them to use their toothbrush five times a week for seven weeks. Then he asked them to tell him how many months they had purchased toothbrushes before getting the one from his practice. If a toothbrush typically costs $2 to purchase, how many months did Dr. Banks test the toothbrushes (the test period)?<n>Rationales: Dr. Banks bought his patients 53 tooth brushes in January and 67 in February, the total number of toothbrushes is 53 + 53 = 166 + 67 = <<166+67=233>>233 tooth brush.<n>The time of use is from January-May = January  + Febuary plus + March plus + April plus+ May. So the total time of use =<<January + February + March + April + May = 5 + 4 + 3 + 2 + 1 = 15>>15 weeks<n>and Dr Banks asks the patient about the period of use ( the test period). The patient tells Dr Banks the tooth brush they used had 20 months and 1 month remaining to use the toothbrush.<n>So the Dr Banks' test period = 5 weeks-(20 months-1month) = 2 months<n>So 233 toothbrush(s) were distributed to the patient for two months. He divided 233/2 =<<233/2=116>>116 toothbrush for each patient to use in two months.<n>#### 116<n>Answer: 116<n>

If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What does a chef do when working in the evening? How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. Choices:  A: sneezing B: fatigue C: house clean D: feeling satisfied E: getting good grades<n><n>### Response:		<n>For (A)<n><n>$sneezing + housework$<n><n>Both of these are random events.<n>To find P(get good grades AND do housework), you can add the probabilities of each event happening separately with AND, but the AND operator combines events such that it has to happen for both of the outcomes to happen, they are dependent so you can't assume P(Get Good Grades) = P(Get Good Gradue and Do Housework).<n>## For (B)<n>`Not E`<n>Fatigue is not a cause of getting good grades, therefore (B) is not an outcome of (A)<n><n>For (C)<n><n>`Not D`<n>Getting good grades does not lead to feeling satisfied or doing house work.<n>## For (D)<n>`P(Getting Good Grades) P(Doing Housework) P(Not getting Good Grades) P (Not doing Housework)`<n>$=P(Getting Good Gradues)$<n>P(Getting Good grades) could result in you doing house work.<n><n>For (E)<n>`P(get Good Grades) P(- doing house work) P(doing house work) P(Not getting good grades)`<n>$= P(Get Good Grdes) $<n>P(Getting good grades) could result of not doing house work.<n>E.<n>P(Not Getting Good Grades)<n>P(Not getting good grdes)<n>$Not Doing House Work$<n><n>### Instructions: Answer the following question in complete sentences.<n>### Instruction Text: After his mother saw his report. he knew he was going.<n><n>### Response Text: He will end up doing house work and get good grades<n><n>#### 1<n><n>### Response 2:<n><n>#### 2:<n>After his mother saw his grades, he knew he was going <n>to end up doing house work, so he did it.<n><n>#### 3<n><n>### C: If the answer is 14. then Sally picks 12?<n><n>### Instructio: <n><n>### Instuction Text:Dr. Bansk picked 32 seashells, then he picks 32/2<n>### Response Text<n><n>Dr. Banspicks

She knows that when a skier accelerates from rest, the coefficient of friction with the ice is 0.7. How fast must the engineer skate to keep her momentum constant if the engineer's mass is 72.8 kg, and she is rolling down the hill at 13.1 m/s?<n><n>### Demisturation:<n>Suppose the engineer is skating at a constant velocity. Let's assume it is at the start of the hill. Then the engineer will initially accelerate at a rate of 9.6 m/s^2, until she reaches the crest of the hill, at which point she reaches constant velocity until she turns around and heads back up the hill (the force of gravity acting upon her will cause her to accelerate upwards.) Note that she will accelerate to her initial velocity, 13.1/t in which [n]=[initial downward velocity].<n>(9.6m/s^2)*(72.8kg)*(t*sin(i)*0.7)*(0.7)*0.15 =[initial downward velocity]<n><n>This is the rate at which the object accelerates.<n><n>### Answer:<n>(13.1/(-3.141*((0.7/13.1)*(9.6m/(t-13.1)*0.7)*72.8/13.1*(1)*0.15))) = <<13.1/((((0.7/9.6)*72.8)/((1)*0.1)(t-13.3)(0.7)))>>(3.141/(9.6*72.8/(((1)*0.7)^(t-13.4)*0.1*(1)*(0.7)+(0.7)/((1)*0.(15-7.4))))))<n><n>Note that in the denominator is 0.7/(((1)*((0.1)/(16.8*((0.7)/(((1)+(15-7.5)))))))) This is simply the skier going down

If he buys 2.5 bananas and 6.5 apples, he will have $0.50 remaining. How much more does he have to spend?<n>```<n>Solution:<n>Answer: 3.5 bananas and one apple<n><n>The total of banana and apple is 9 bananas. and the total of amount that James pay is banana + apple + leftover = 39.5.<n>The missing apple is 39.5 - 9 = <<39.5-9 = 30>>30.<n>The missing banana is 39. 5 - 6.5 = <<39.95=39>>39.<n>The banana he bought is 2.5.<n>He must pay for 3.5 banana to be full. <n>The apple he bought is six.<n>He must pay five dollar + 0.25 to be full.<n>```<n><n>### Input James wants to buy 4 bananas, 5 apples, and 2 oranges. Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:Where would you sit in a chair to watch four-legged animals complete? Choices:  A: bookstore B: house C: race track D: friend's house E: building<n><n>### Response:		Bookstore<n><n>#### Solution:<n><n>In the above image given there are three animals and they are in a row where they are placed,<n><n>**Question:What animal did not come when the whistle blew the whistle?**<n><n>Here when the whistle is blown the rabbit stops and donkey also stops. Because the donkey is going right direction and the rabbit is going left direction. So both of them are in the correct direction to complete the task. Now the dog is going too far from the direction of the whistle.<n><n>**Question:**<n><n>Which animal is in the correct position to listen to the whistle?<n>**Solution:**<n>In the above image, you will see the rabbit is the correct position to listen because he is on a 45-degree angle. So he can hear the whistle easily. So you can choose option B<n><n>**Question:The animal that cannot hear the whistle is in________?**<n>**Solution: Bookstore<n>Because dogs can hear the whistles. In a bookstore, nobody can hear the whistling because it is quite<n><n>### Output: The solution is the right one.<n><n><n><n>

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:What could a balalaika be needed for? How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:The woman picked from an apple tree while surrounded by other trees, where was she? Choices:  A: illinois B: woods C: new york D: indiana E: farmer's market<n><n>### Response:		<n>  -<n>####  E<n>#### Answer:  E<n>Input: The woman picked from an apple<n>Rationales: <n>* <n><n>The woman picked from an Apple tree, and we're supposed to guess her location.<n>The only choice that mentions the word apple is  E: farmer' s market.<n><n>### Disclaimer<n><n>Please note that we aren't claiming credit for any material or content created by the authors of the videos you watch.<n>

He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:The whole family was playing cards, they were full of joy and what? Choices:  A: sadness B: happiness C: amusement D: losing money E: anger<n><n>### Response:		Answer the following multiple  choices question.<n><n>## Input:The whole family  was playing cards, they  were full of joy and...  A: sadness    B: Happiness    C: Amusement    D: Losing money    E: Anger<n><n>Demonstration:<n>#### A<n>Joy is not a choice I'm afraid of you can be a little bit upset but not sadness.<n>#### B<n>Happiness is a great choice!<n>#### C<n>Amusement would include laughing, smiling and being silly which is probably really bad if playing cards?<n>#### E<n>Sorry we cannot answer this, we do not want anger in our response!<n><n>#### 3<n>Answer: 4<n>##

How long has every Tuesday passed?<n>Rationales:: Five Thursdays passed in one year = <<5*Tuesday+ Thursday>>5*Tuesday +Thursday=365 days<n>In one year there are 365/52=6<n>Thus, 6 Tuesdays pass per year.<n>We observe that if there are 360 days in a year, then 360/52=7 Tuesdays pass per in a year.<n>If we count 7 Tuesdays per year, we can expect that when we meet our friends after vacation, it is Tuesday again.<n><n>#### 7<n>Answer: 7<n><n>#### 7/ 52<n>I do not know when the correct answer is 7 or 7/52.

There is rarely if ever any stress and worry because there are not assignments and expectations, however there is still school work for children to do, if the parents and/or teachers have allowed that for any reason to happen for example, parents may think it is a good or important idea for their children to get some school work out of the way before their vacation or a holiday.<n><n>However I did not mention a school lunch, a school lunch is a great time to bond and get social with other children, even though it is not the biggest thing on their mind, they still have one to two hours to be with other children without any homework, or other assignments (like the rest of the time at school.)<n><n>#### 4) Provide the rational for the ones you marked incorrect.<n><n>Answer: E: Dinner<n><n>The reason E: Dinner is wrong, is because a school lunch is when they bond or get social with other people and are free to spend that time with other people, rather than worrying about what else they can or can not achieve at school.<n><n>#### 5) If you had more time to review the assessment, what would you change?<n><n>Answer: I would not have chosen A toy store.<n><n>### Input :<n>How many times (if applicable, please explain how to account for this variation) was it more than the median?<n>Choice: (if applicable, please provide rationales.
Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:How can you get in shape if there is no land nearby? If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Rationales: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>#### 54<n>Answer: 54<n><n>### Input:When they got out of the car in the mountains he felt like he was breathing fresh air for the first time, he began to do what to enjoy it more?
